04909nam a22004815i 9780804780933DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20222002cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047809337 a10.1515/97808047809332doi  a(DE-B1597)581717  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aHN385 7aHIS0150002bisacsh04a361.610941222/ger1 aRoberts, F. David, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Social Conscience of the Early Victorians /cF. David Roberts. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2022] 4c©2002  a1 online resource (584 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgments -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tPART I: THE TRADITION OF PATERNALISM -- t1. The Idea of Paternalism -- t2. Paternalism Made Popular -- t3. The Practice of Paternalism -- tPART II: THE VISION OF A LAISSEZ-FAIRE SOCIETY -- t4. The Triumph of Political Economy -- t5. The Impact of Political Economy -- t6. Sacred Property and Divine Providence -- t7. Self-Reliance -- t8. Voluntarism -- tPART III: BASIC ATTITUDES -- t9. Philanthropy -- t10. Humanitarianism -- t11. The Sources of Humanitarianism -- t12. Vested, Class, and Self-Interest -- tPART IV: THE ROLE OF GOVERNMENT -- t13. Government a Vast Evil -- t14. The Inexorable Growth of Government -- t15. The Idea of a Paternal Government -- t16. The Idea of a Utilitarian State -- tConclusion -- tAppendix: M.P.'s of Religious and Rationalist Outlook -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 1830, the dominant social outlook of the early Victorians was a paternalism that looked to property, the Church, and local Justices of the Peace to govern society and deal with its ills. By 1860, however, the dominant social outlook had become a vision of a laissez faire society that relied on economic laws, self-reliance, and the vigorous philanthropy of voluntary societies. This book describes and analyzes these changes, which arose from the rapid growth of industry, towns, population, and the middle and working classes. Paternalism did not entirely fade away, however, just as a laissez faire vision had long antedated 1830. Both were part of a social conscience also defined by a revived philanthropy, a new humanitarianism, and a grudging acceptance of an expanded government, all of which reflected a strong revival of religion as well as the growth of rationalism. The new dominance of a laissez faire vision was dramatically evident in the triumph of political economy. By 1860, only a few doubted the eternal verities of the economists’ voluminous writings. Few also doubted the verities of those who preached self-reliance, who supported the New Poor Law’s severity to persons who were not self-reliant, and who inspired education measures to promote that indispensable virtue. If economic laws and self-reliance failed to prevent distress, the philanthropists and voluntary societies would step in. Such a vision proved far more buoyant and effective than a paternalism whose narrow and rural Anglican base made it unable to cope with the downside of an industrial-urban Britain. But the vision of a laissez faire society was not without its flaws. Its harmonious economic laws and its hope in self-reliance did not prevent gross exploitation and acute distress, and however beneficent were its philanthropists, they fell far short of mitigating these evils. This vision also found a rival in an expanded government. Two powerful ideas—the idea of a paternal government and the idea of a utilitarian state—helped create the expansion of government services. A reluctant belief in governmental power thus joined the many other ideas that defined the Victorian’s social conscience.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aCharitieszGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 0aPaternalismzGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 4aHistory -- British. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080478093340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804780933423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780804780933/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles